				\begin{document}$${{{{{{{\mathcal{O}}}}}}}}({(3NM)}^{3})$$\end{document}. Moreover, BIGDML is trained in closed-form (via matrix decomposition), which requires storing the kernel matrix at O((3NM)2)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{{{{{{\mathcal{O}}}}}}}}({(3NM)}^{2})$$\end{document} memory cost. The inclusion of symmetries only incurs extra linear cost during kernel matrix construction in this scenario, while the training cost remains the same. These economics are ideal for the application to periodic systems, where we can impose a strong inductive prior through the inclusion of large symmetry sets, which allows the number of training points M to remain small. Now, in cases where memory limitations appear, the model can be trained by a numerical solver as in the case of neural networks. This approach allows training much larger models and bigger systems.

